data.description:
To do this kata you must have completed [#1](https://www.codewars.com/kata/5c8f822533a2b7336aeee2de) part.

In this kata we will use the `create` function from [#1](https://www.codewars.com/kata/5c8f822533a2b7336aeee2de) to create some interesting observables that, in turn, will serve us in the rest of the series kata.

To complete this kata you may have to improve the version you gave in kata [#1](https://www.codewars.com/kata/5c8f822533a2b7336aeee2de).

Let's start.

# of observable

Emit variable amount of values in a sequence and then emits a `complete` notification.

```typescript
declare function of<T>(...xs: T[]): Observable<T>

const source = of(1, 2, 3, 4, 5);
//output: 1,2,3,4,5,"completed"
const subscribe = source.subscribe({onNext: val => console.log(val), onComplete: () => console.log("completed")});
```

# empty observable

Observable that immediately completes.

```typescript
declare function empty<T>(): Observable<T>

//output: 'Complete!'
const subscribe = empty().subscribe({
  onNext: () => console.log('Next'),
  onComplete: () => console.log('Complete!')
});
```

# interval observable

Emit numbers in sequence based on provided timeframe. Never complete!

```typescript
declare function interval(period: number): Observable<number>

//emit value in sequence every 1 second
const source = interval(1000);
//output: 0,1,2,3,4,5....
const subscribe = source.subscribe({onNext: val => console.log(val)});
```

CAUTION: Interval never completes, but Codewars does not finish running the tests if there are pending timers. To avoid timeouts you must unsubscribe from observable interval. See test section.


# from event

Turn event into observable sequence.

```typescript
declare funtion fromEvent = (
  element: EventEmitter,
  eventName: string
): Observable<Event>

class MyEmitter extends EventEmitter {}
const myEmitter = new MyEmitter();
//emit value in sequence every 1 second
const source = fromEvent(myEmitter, "event");

// output: an event occurred
const subscribe = source.subscribe({onNext: val => console.log(val)});

myEmitter.emit('event', 'an event occurred');
```

[See](https://nodejs.org/api/events.html) Node EventEmitters docs.


When you have finished, you can continue with [#3 Premier operators](https://www.codewars.com/kata/5c914f2ae041fe000e8964ee)
